icers than previous historians have allowed, and suggests that the UVF was quite capable of seizing control of Ulster and installing the Ulster Provisional Government in the event of Home Rule being implemented in 1914.This book will be essential reading for military and Irish historians and their students, and will interest any general reader interested in modern paramilitary forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aIreland-History-1910-1921. 0aIreland-Politics and government-1910-1921. 0aUlster Volunteer Force (1913-1920). 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Ireland.2bisacsh  aAndrew Bonar Law.  aBritish public opinion.  aIrish revolutionary period.  aLiberal government.  aNationalist Ireland.  aOrange Order.  aSir Edward Carson.  aThird Home Rule crisis.  aUVF equipment.  aUlster Special Constabulary.  aUlster Unionist militancy.  aUlster Volunteer Force.  aUnionist Clubs.  aUnionist propaganda.  aarmed Unionism.  amilitary efficiency units.  aneo-feudalism.  apolitical ideology.  astandard military hierarchy.1 aBowman, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez9783111283630oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129567/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPc1986d2013